{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"255f28bb-afe4-4982-b7c4-f5f3d73a30c6","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**You can also use Console.app:**\n- Open **Console** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n\n**To get a core dump instead**, enable them before running:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nCore files go to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nOnce you have the `.ips` file, you can symbolicate the .NET runtime frames to get source-level info. Want help with that?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a502e1fb-ac4b-4849-b900-17c1151e414f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":278,"requestId":"A0C8:200D30:91177E:B360E5:6A01366D"},"id":"7e871d19-b83c-435e-b93f-e04ab480065e","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:54.618Z","parentId":"7a964828-9ce8-4bb6-928f-a47c73071647"}
